<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-102-760  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 102 760.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Jan 29 1990 v218 n5 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. changes its position on exports to Eastern Europe. (hightechnology) (News of the Week)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Bush administration will propose a relaxation of the rulesthat prevent export of high technology to Eastern Europe.andP;  Thechange would ease sales restrictions to six Eastern Europeannations: at first, Hungary and Poland would benefit; later, EastGermany and Czechoslovakia would be included; and finally, Romaniaand Bulgaria.andP;  The administration will present its plan at ameeting of the Coordinating Committee on Multilateral ExportControls (Cocom), to be held in Feb 1990.andP;  Cocom, which hasblocked such sales in the past, is a group of 17 nonCommunistindustrial nations.andP;  A spokesperson for the 3500-member AmericanElectronics Association (AEA), which has pushed for such a change,is cautious because details of the government's plan are not yetknown.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United StatesHigh TechnologyInternational tradeAmerican Electronics AssociationUnited States. Department of StateCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsComputer industryTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>